@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_17" " Re: Digest Number 142 "
From: Bob Lanham <bobl@jaxproductions.com>
Date: 09-10-99 14:12:24
Subject: @{b}Re: Digest Number 142@{ub}

From: Bob Lanham <bobl@jaxproductions.com>

> _______________________________________________________________________________
> 
>    Date: Thu, 9 Sep 1999 18:08:43 (-0600)
>    From: Laura Vance <vancel@amiga.nols.com>
> Subject: Using Datatypes
> 
> The way that I've gathered to use the datatypes is the following sequence:
> 
> NewDTObject()
> // create the window that will be used for output
> if(object)
> {
>     AddDTObject()
>     DoDTMethod()        // can I do more than one method per statement?
>     RefreshDTObjectA()
> }

Laura,
I think the reason it won't display is you left out SetDTAttrs(), which
goes before AddDTObject().  See my example below.  I've learned that
there are 2 ways to show the DataType Picture: 1. Use AddDTObject(). or
2. BltBitMapRastPort().  I will include an example of each method below.


>    Date: Fri, 10 Sep 1999 03:40:16 +0200 (METDST)
>    From: Nicholas Clarke <nclarke@diku.dk>
> Subject: Re: Using Datatypes
> 
> Datatypes dont do any on screen redering. You still have to copy the
> data with bltbitmap.
> 
As I wrote above, DataTypes will do the screen rendering if done a
certain way.  But there's nothing wrong with the Blitting method.  It's
just 2 different approaches!  Once again see below.


/***********************************************************************/
/**** METHOD 1: using AddDTObject() (parts were deleted to
shorten)*****/
/**** Notice no DoDTMethod() is required.
******************************/

    Object *mypic=NULL;
    ULONG w,h;

if(mypic = NewDTObject(filename,
    DTA_SourceType,  DTST_FILE,    /* source is a file */
    DTA_GroupID,     GID_PICTURE,  /* must be a picture */
    PDTA_Remap,      FALSE,
    TAG_DONE))
    {

    /* get attributes we are interested in */
    GetDTAttrs(mypic,
        DTA_NominalHoriz,     &w,
        DTA_NominalVert,      &h,
        TAG_DONE);

        /* set the attributes of our datatype object*/
        /* here's what you left out! */
        SetDTAttrs(mypic,NULL,NULL,
            GA_Left,    0,
            GA_Top,     0,
            GA_Width,   w,
            GA_Height,  h,
            TAG_DONE);

        AddDTObject(window1,NULL,mypic,-1);
        Delay(20); /* Probably not the best way to wait. */
        RefreshDTObjects(mypic,window1,NULL,NULL);
        RemoveDTObject(window1,mypic);
        DisposeDTObject(mypic);
        }
/****************************************************************/

/** METHOD 2: The blitting method (again, parts have been cut)****/
/** Notice you must get the PDTA_BitMap, and DoDTMethod() ******/

    Object *mypic=NULL;
    ULONG w,h;
    struct BitMap *bm;

if(mypic = NewDTObject(filename,
    DTA_SourceType,  DTST_FILE,    /* source is a file */
    DTA_GroupID,     GID_PICTURE,  /* make sure it's a picture */
    PDTA_Remap,      FALSE,
    TAG_DONE))
    {

    DoDTMethod(mypic,NULL,NULL,DTM_PROCLAYOUT,TAG_DONE);

    /* get attributes we are interested in */
    GetDTAttrs(mypic,
        DTA_NominalHoriz, &w,
        DTA_NominalVert,  &h,
        PDTA_BitMap,      &bm,
        TAG_DONE);

        /* blit bitmap into window */
        BltBitMapRastPort(bm,0,0,window1->RPort,
                                 window1->BorderLeft,
                                 window1->BorderTop,
                                 w,h,0xC0);

    /* Notice we don't RemoveDTObject(window1,mypic) */
    /* since we never did AddDTObject().*/
    DisposeDTObject(mypic);
    }
/****************************************************************/

@ENDNODE
