@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_37" " Re: fread and windowhandling at the same time "
From: Andrew Bell <andrew.ab2000@bigfoot.com>
Date: 09-16-99 00:29:39
Subject: @{b}Re: fread and windowhandling at the same time@{ub}

From: Andrew Bell <andrew.ab2000@bigfoot.com>

Hi Fritsch,

On 15-Sep-99, you wrote:

> I am writing a program that processes an audio file and displays for
> example the spectrum. This works fine. But now it comes to
> Amiga-specific stuff.
> 
> [snip]
> 
> Now my problem: How can I combine these two loops in an effective,
> amiga-like manner?
> I want to process the file and want to be able to handle
> Window-Events at the same time...
> 
> Any ideas?

Don't use Wait() in your loop, instead use dos.library/CheckSignal() to check for any signals you need to act on. Or if you only want to catch the IDCMP event happening at your window, use gadtools.library/ GT_GetIMsg() on your window's message port. If the result of this call is non-NULL, then you know that an IDCMP message is waiting at your window's port.

So for example:

fopen();
while (fread(...))
{
    DoAndDisplayFourierTransformation(Sample);

    IMsg = GT_GetIMsg( YourWindow->UserPort );

    if ( IMsg )
    {
        CopyMem( IMsg, CopyOfIMsg, sizeof(struct IntuiMessage) );

        GT_ReplyIMsg( IMsg );

        ProcessIDCMPMessage( CopyOfIMsg );
    }
}
fclose();

This is just a simple example, note that this loop will eat up a lot of CPU cycles, it might be a good idea to keep your task priority low. Or some form on an async IO approach might be better.

Regards, Andrew Bell.
-- 

