On Tue, 7 Sep 1999, Dominic Clifton wrote:

> Is it me, or on an 8 colour screen the ANSI escape sequence
> <esc>[0m should return the foreground (text) colour to 7 (white) and
> not 1 (red) ?

Possibly, but you should probably find the relevant ANSI standard.
I can't remember the number of it.

> Is it possible to fix this by way of patching the console device ?
> 
> How do you grab a shared library or device from the rom so that you
> can patch it to make a disk based version (under a different name or not) ?

You can't.  Disk-based modules are relocatable whereas ROM modules run
from a fixed address.

Ben.


@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_42" " Re: HD Trouble "
From: Ben Hutchings <benh@cnct.com>
Date: 09-16-99 00:51:28
Subject: @{b}Re: HD Trouble@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <benh@cnct.com>

On Sun, 5 Sep 1999, Laura Vance wrote:

> From: Laura Vance <vancel@amiga.nols.com>
> 
> There is a program on AmiNet that will get your RDB information.  I had
> that same problem happen a few months ago.  I am using a 10GB hard drive
> and for some reason the format command messed up the RDB.

You should not use the Format command on HDs without the "quick" option. 
There is no need to format hard drives, and the driver will treat a
TD_FORMAT command just like a CMD_WRITE command.  The real problem is that
these commands are limited to the first 4 GB of the disk.  You have to use
different commands on big disks.

I wrote a replacement for Format, called BHFormat, which knows about the
64-bit commands and checks for many nasty error conditions.  You can find
it on Aminet in the util/sys directory.

> But it messed it up because I was still using my compuer whil it was
> formatting another partition on my drive. 
<snip>

I don't think that has anything to do with it.


