@NODE "Mail_47" " Re: An interesting problem "
From: Michael_Sage@May-Co.com
Date: 09-16-99 14:55:09
Subject: @{b}Re: An interesting problem@{ub}

From: Michael_Sage@May-Co.com



I think you have two problems here:

1.  main() returning void.  If you don't explicitly return something back to the
operating system, the compiler will generate the code to return a value.  The
standard does not specify how this is to be done so, it's up to the compiler
writer.  I've been bitten by this.  Our C++ compiler on our mainframe will
generate code that causes an abend.  You should re-code main() as:

int main(void)
  {
     .
     .
     .
     return 0;            // or exit(0);
  }

2.  Somewhere your object is getting copied or you have a pointer to your
object.  Your second "Destructor finished" is either coming from the object's
copy going out of scope (which I doubt--you should see a second "Constructor
finished"--but, I'm still new at C++) or, the pointer is being deleted after the
object falls out of scope (deleting a pointer to an object implicitly calls the
object's destructor--which, if the object has already been "destructed" can
cause undefined behavior, like abends).  I'm leaning towards a pointer problem.

Hope this helps.


Michael S. Sage





@ENDNODE
