@NODE "Mail_49" " Re: fread and windowhandling at the same time "
From: Andrew Bell <andrew.ab2000@bigfoot.com>
Date: 09-16-99 16:29:24
Subject: @{b}Re: fread and windowhandling at the same time@{ub}

From: Andrew Bell <andrew.ab2000@bigfoot.com>

Hi Fritsch,

On 16-Sep-99, you wrote:

>     Thanks to Andrew and Allan for the answers. The example above is
> easy to understand and I will propably do my program in this way.
> But you and Allan mentioned Async IO. What do mean? Could you give
> me an (pseudocode) example for Async IO too?

Async IO is a bit complicated, so I'll try to explain it instead of
giving you an example.

Basically when you read some data from a file, you would normally use
fread(...) or dos.library/Read(), the problem with these functions is
they "block" your task until the read operation is finished. The idea
behind async IO is to let your task get on with other things, instead of
waiting around for an IO operation to finish.

One way to get around this is to mess around with DOS packets and
issue commands directly to the filesystem handler, but you're better
off using the async IO routines provided by Commodore.

For more detailed information refer to Fast AmigaDOS IO chapter in the
Amiga Mail Volume II (this is on the Amiga Dev CD 1.2).

IIRC, there's an async IO library on Aminet in dev/c, this might be
useful for your needs.

Regards, Andrew Bell.
-- 

