@NODE "Mail_71" " Re: FPrintf() and VFPrintf() "
From: Andrew Bell <andrew.ab2000@bigfoot.com>
Date: 09-24-99 06:13:50
Subject: @{b}Re: FPrintf() and VFPrintf()@{ub}

From: Andrew Bell <andrew.ab2000@bigfoot.com>

Hi W1bBle,

On 24-Sep-99, you wrote:

> Could someone please tell me what the difference is between these
> two functions and give me an example of how to call them properly. I
> can't make any sense of the Autodocs, and all I get is a text file
> with a lot zeros in it when I use them! :(

VFPrintf() and FPrintf() are exactly the same, except that FPrintf() is the varargs version, ie: it pushes the parameters onto the stack. VFPrintf() is the actual LVO, and is really for assembly users. When using C, try to stick with FPrintf(), if possible.

So with FPrintf() you'd call it like this:

  FPrintf(FH, "string %ld %ld %ld %ld %ld\n", 1, 2, 3, 4, 5);

But for VFPrintf() you need to call it like this:

  ULONG fmtdata[] = 
  {
    1, 2, 3, 4, 5
  };
 
  VFPrintf(FH, "string %ld %ld %ld %ld %ld\n", &fmtdata);

And don't forget, never use these functions with ANSI style file
handles (ie: FILE *). They are for AmigaDOS filehandles only (ie: Open()) and not ANSI ones (ie: fopen()).

This should be what you're looking for (if I haven't made any typos :)

void update_stack_representation(void) 
{
  int count;
  BPTR OutFH;  
 
  OutFH = Open("ram:example.txt", MODE_NEWFILE);

  if (OutFH)
  {
    if (Is_Empty(MachG.p_G_Stack)==FALSE)
    {
      for (count=0; count<=MachG.p_G_Stack->TOS; count++)
      {
        FPrintf(OutFH, "%d ",MachG.p_G_Stack->stack_array[count]);
      }
      FPrintf(OutFH, "\n");
    }
    else FPrintf(OutFH, "\n");

    Close(OutFH);
  }
}


Regards, Andrew Bell.
-- 

