@NODE "Mail_75" " About the UDS-Amiga list & UDS "
From: David Arbuthnot <Trebor@Digital.Prestel.co.uk>
Date: 09-24-99 16:22:26
Subject: @{b}About the UDS-Amiga list & UDS@{ub}

From: David Arbuthnot <Trebor@Digital.Prestel.co.uk>

Hello,
My name is David Arbuthnot and I've started a list (with one-list ) because
I am in the process of creating a filefomat for use on the Amiga
(and other platforms eventualy). A brief description of this fileformat is
below, but you can mail me for more detailed info.

I'd just like to invite anyone who is interested to subscribe to
UDS-Amiga because I think the UDS fileformat will become very popular
eventually (and I sick of talking to myself about it).

send an email to UDS-Amiga-subscribe@onelist.com to subscribe

A Brief Description of the UDS FileFormat
-----------------------------------------

UDS is sort of like a shell for storing data in an effective way.
UDS stores data in pools & pools are contained in nodes so that 
file data is organized and easy to read into your program.
A node would (yep I feel a diagram coming on) look like this in diagram
form:

NODENAME
NODEID
POOLTABLEOFFSET

a node can contain any number of pools you like therefore pools are not
actually contained in the nodes themselfs, instead a node
contains a pointer to a table of pool offsets. so lets just say you wanted
to store a song in a UDS file you could have two nodes
one that contained a pool for your pattern/block data for your song
(BPM,note data,etc...) and then the other that contained a number of pools
for each sample. So the file would look something like this:

UDSHEADER

NODE1
NODENAME
NODEID
PTO (POOL TABLE OFFSET)

NODE2
NODENAME
NODEID
PTO

NODETABLE (see blow for more about this)

POOLTABLE FOR NODE 1
POOLTABLE FOR NODE 2

POOL1 FOR NODE 1 (note data,BPM,etc...)
POOLNAME
POOLID
POOLINFOOFFSET
POOLDATAOFFSET

POOL1 FOR NODE 2 (First Sample)
POOLNAME
POOLID
POOLINFOOFFSET
POOLDATAOFFSET

POOL2 FOR NODE 2 (Second Sample)
POOLNAME
POOLID
POOLINFOOFFSET
POOLDATAOFFSET

POOLn FOR NODE 2 (n'th Sample)
POOLNAME
POOLID
POOLINFOOFFSET
POOLDATAOFFSET

POOLINFO FOR NODE 1 - POOL 1
POOLINFO FOR NODE 2 - POOL 1
POOLINFO FOR NODE 2 - POOL 2
POOLINFO FOR NODE 2 - POOL n

POOLDATA FOR NODE 1 - POOL 1
POOLDATA FOR NODE 2 - POOL 1
POOLDATA FOR NODE 2 - POOL 2
POOLDATA FOR NODE 2 - POOL n 

So first we have the UDS header this contains info about the file & it's
contents (Author,Copyright,Version,etc...) a SubType Identifier (in this
case it would be somthing like UDS_SubType_MySong. Well somthing like that)
and a node table offset which is just like a pooltable offset execept it
points to a table of node pointers.

Then we have our nodes which contain a name (NODE1 could have the name
"TRACKERDATA" and node 2 could have the name SAMPLES) and ID (1 - n, n
being as many as you like) and a PTO (pooltableoffset) which points to a
pooltable for this node.

Then we have the nodetable which contains pointers to all the nodes before
it. The node table is used so we can find 1 node (useful if the file
contains many nodes).

Then we have a pooltable for each of our nodes. Each pooltable contains
pointers to all of the pools in the node that the pooltable belongs to.

Next comes the pools themselfs which contain (like the nodes) a name and ID
(since in this example we are storing one sample in each pool the name of
the pool could be the name of the sample) pools alos contain pointers to 2
structures the first structure is called PoolInfo a poolinfo structure
contains information that is needed in order for the program to read the
pool data correctly (in this example it would contain info about the
plaback rate of the sample,loop points,etc...) and the other structure is
called PoolData which is self explanatory as its name reflects what it
contins (The Sample Data in this example).

and finally we have the poolinfo structures for each pool and then the data
for each pool

Now that was a brief explanation of the UDS Fileformat for a more detailed
explanation e-mail me at Trebor@Digital.Prestel.co.uk with the subjectline
containing "UDS - Detailed Explanation" and the body containg any questions
about UDS that you may have.

Kind regards,
    Trebor (List Owner of UDS-Amiga)

@ENDNODE
