@NODE "Mail_80" " Re: About the UDS-Amiga list & UDS "
From: David Arbuthnot <Trebor@Digital.Prestel.co.uk>
Date: 09-25-99 01:31:28
Subject: @{b}Re: About the UDS-Amiga list & UDS@{ub}

From: David Arbuthnot <Trebor@Digital.Prestel.co.uk>

On 24-Sep-99, Michael_Sage@May-Co.com wrote:
> 
> How is this different from IFF? I'm no expert on IFF but, except for the
> author info. in the header, this sounds like IFF.
> 

Well, It may sound like IFF for the simple reason that UDS is based on a
number of different fileformats such as IFF,MMD's (OctaMED modules), HTML,
WAV's and loads more. There are some big differences (Really BIG) for
instance since more than one type of data can be stored in a UDS file you
can use different types of compression and encryption for different parts
of the file e.g say you want to store an animation you are going to want to
store sounds as well as images but at times an animation can get quite
large (24-bit Images & 16 bit sound for example can be Really BIG) so
ideally you would compress the file after it had been saved to disk using
XPK or PowerPacker or somthing like that but UDS handles all this
transparently. Different types of data compress better/worse depending on
the algorithim used to compress the data so UDS chooses the best
compression it can depending on the type of data that needs to be
compressed. On another note I am very organised with my data and I'm sick
to death (almost otherwise I wouldn't be typing this) of having loads of
different fileformats laying around on my harddrive so I thought why not
create a fileformat that can store any type of data weather it be 24-bit
video with 16-bit sound or an ASCII textfile. See in theory you could store
all your datafiles in one HUGE UDS file (not really a good idea a seeking
for data would be S L O W). As an example say you were creating a sample
editor and you wanted to read samples out of a MOD or whatever and save
them back you would have to read the entire MOD decode all the samples
separate effects data and so on but with UDS you just look into a node that
contains samples and load whichever samples you wanted which sounds easier
???. Also please note that UDS in still in very early stages of dvelopment
therefore much of the above is still not implemented.

Regards,
    Dave "Trebor" Arbuthnot.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_81" " Re: Re: About the UDS-Amiga list & UDS "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
