> Well, It may sound like IFF for the simple reason that UDS is based on a
> number of different fileformats such as IFF,MMD's (OctaMED modules), HTML,
> WAV's and loads more. There are some big differences (Really BIG) for
> instance since more than one type of data can be stored in a UDS file

It's quite possible to store multiple kinds of data in an IFF file.

> you can use different types of compression and encryption for
> different parts of the file

> e.g say you want to store an animation you are going to want to
> store sounds as well as images but at times an animation can get
> quite large (24-bit Images & 16 bit sound for example can be Really
> BIG) so ideally you would compress the file after it had been saved
> to disk using XPK or PowerPacker or somthing like that but UDS
> handles all this transparently.

Is UDS a file format or a piece of software?

> Different types of data compress better/worse depending on
> the algorithim used to compress the data so UDS chooses the best
> compression it can depending on the type of data that needs to be
> compressed.

That's absurd.  That depends on just what the creator wants to do
with the data.

> On another note I am very organised with my data and I'm sick
> to death (almost otherwise I wouldn't be typing this) of having loads of
> different fileformats laying around on my harddrive

So why create another one?  We already have plenty of file formats
with all the features you're talking about.

> so I thought why not create a fileformat that can store any type of
> data weather it be 24-bit video with 16-bit sound or an ASCII
> textfile.

Different types of data logically need different formats.  I think
what you're talking about is general structures for files, and we
already have plenty of those.  Quicktime is great for audio and video
and XML is great for text.

> See in theory you could store
> all your datafiles in one HUGE UDS file (not really a good idea a seeking
> for data would be S L O W). As an example say you were creating a sample
> editor and you wanted to read samples out of a MOD or whatever and save
> them back you would have to read the entire MOD decode all the samples
> separate effects data and so on but with UDS you just look into a node that
> contains samples and load whichever samples you wanted which sounds easier
> ???. Also please note that UDS in still in very early stages of dvelopment
> therefore much of the above is still not implemented.

Please, don't waste your time.  Learn more about what's already out
there, and put your efforts into supporting existing good formats.

