@NODE "Mail_94" " Amiga OS C++ classes "
From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>
Date: 09-27-99 23:57:50
Subject: @{b}Amiga OS C++ classes@{ub}

From: Ben Hutchings <womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk>

Some time ago I started on a project to create replacement header
files for AmigaOS development that would define the OS structures
using C++ extensions, including member functions.  This is similar
to the work Laurie Perrin has done, but more ambitious.

The new header files (one per non-nested class) correctly represent
the inheritance relationships that exist in the OS, restrictions on
access and const-ness, the types of BPTR targets and of list nodes.
This should allow for more natural manipulation of OS objects, and
should remove much of the need for ugly, error-prone casting when
dealing with the OS APIs.

Member functions are mostly short inline functions - in most cases
they are OS library calls.  Library calls are themselves inline member
functions of library classes.  So a good compiler should add little or
no overhead to OS calls.

For debugging purposes, you can use alternative versions of most
functions which are not compiled inline and which have many run-time
checks to catch errors that would otherwise crash the system.

This is the theory.  In practice, this is a very large job, and I
don't know whether it's worth completing.  I certainly don't believe I
can complete it on my own.  If you're interested in using or joining
this project, please tell me.

-- 
Ben Hutchings - womble@zzumbouk.demon.co.uk, http://www.zzumbouk.demon.co.uk
Team *AMIGA* | Jay Miner Society | Linux - the choice of a GNU generation
To err is human; to really foul things up requires a computer.

