@NODE "Mail_99" " RE: fooling boot "
From: Jesper Svennevid <jesper@fxrealm.com>
Date: 09-29-99 13:26:38
Subject: @{b}RE: fooling boot@{ub}

From: "Jesper Svennevid" <jesper@fxrealm.com>

> I have now two bootable partitions (os3.1 and os3.5) and I'm quite tired
> to use bootmenu every time to choose the boot partition. I've tried to
> change sys: and other vital assings in startup sequence after mouse button
> test, but it doesn't seem to do the trick 100%tly. Is there any way to
> solve this, maybe using some reset resident code?

Just write a small program that tests if the left mb is pressed, and if so,
return warn(5). then you can for example make some kind of toggle(see below)
that assigns SYS: to another partition(and any other assigns that seem to
resolve before your program can kick in and execute the new startup-sequence
and then terminate this one. I tried this for a booting from another
partition
when it existed, and it worked just fine.

The following SHOULD allow you to swap boot whenever you want, and then let
it
stay at what you selected at reboots, no need to go through the bootmenu.

MouseTest.c:

//ok, hw banging, but if you want to write a input-handler for this,
//be my guest :)

unsigned char* mbutton = (unsigned char*)0xbfe001;


int main(int argc, char* argv[])
{
	return (64==(mbutton&64))?0:5;
}

and the script in your startup-sequence:

MouseTest
IF WARN
   IF EXISTS S:OtherBoot
      Delete S:OtherBoot
   ELSE
      Echo 1 > S:OtherBoot
   ENDIF
ENDIF

IF EXISTS S:OtherBoot
   Assign SYS: MyOtherPartition:
   Assign C: SYS:C
   Assign S: SYS:S
   ; check what other assigns you need to redirect to the
   ; new partition

   Execute S:startup-sequence
   endcli >NIL:
ENDIF

--
// Jesper Svennevid : jesper@fxrealm.com

